================================================================================
Prior art and attributions
================================================================================

xRenderEngine reimplements techniques described in several prior terminal-
rendering projects. Except where noted below, the reimplementation is at the
level of *technique and prose*, not source code; no third-party source is
copied.

- asciimare (MIT) — voxel raycaster + precomputed glyph-luminance table. Our
  luminance-ramp model and font-coverage calibration follow its approach. We
  ship *measured numbers*, never font outlines.

- Ymael (C++/ncurses) — programmable-pipeline rasterizer (vertex/fragment
  stages, depth buffer, OBJ loader). Techniques referenced; its lack of near-
  plane clipping is explicitly avoided.

- Command_Line_3D (C++/Windows) — functional pixel-shader console API
  (FillRectangle(lambda)), double-buffered presentation, ECS scene views and a
  frame pacer. Techniques referenced (the `fill_with` debug API, the frame
  pacer, the single-present diff).

- justMoritz / 3d-game-engine (JS, javidx9 lineage) — grid raycasting and text
  presentation. Concept-level reference only; the grid raycaster's true vertical
  pitch fixes its row-shift artifact.

- "The Algorithm for Painting With ASCII Characters" by Alex Harri — the 6-D
  shape-vector glyph-selection technique with per-component normalization and
  contrast enhancement. Reimplemented from the article's prose; no code reuse.

- gemini-engine (MIT, Ren "renpenguin") — evaluated and rejected as a base
  dependency (see RiftEngine-Plan/14-gemini-engine-analysis.md). Its **ear-
  clipping triangulator** is vendored (re-implemented and hardened) in
  `xre-cello/src/triangulate.rs`; its lint set, `WrappingMode` plot policy and
  adapter-canvas API patterns inspired the corresponding code. gemini-engine is
  MIT-licensed:

